## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow + ResetAbort.

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|----------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Never triggered — the exception type still exists but is never thrown |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running, accept a token

The above is a drop-in replacement, but **cooperative cancellation only works if the work checks the token**. For CPU-bound work:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the work delegate keeps running until it hits a cancellation checkpoint. `Task.WaitAsync` returns to the *caller* promptly, but the background work continues silently. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer leaks. Always `using`. |
| **Uncooperative code won't stop** | If `work` calls a blocking native/third-party API that never checks the token, it will run to completion. For truly uncooperative code, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures only *your* timeout triggers the `TimeoutException` — other cancellations propagate normally. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** | Available on your target (.NET 8). No backport needed. |

### What was removed and why

| Original | Removed because | Replaced with |
|----------|----------------|---------------|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | Manual thread management | `Task.Run` (uses ThreadPool) |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | Blocking wait with no cancellation | `Task.WaitAsync(token)` |
| `thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` (via constructor) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in .NET 8 | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 | Not needed — cooperative model has no abort to reset |
